<p><strong>The 100: A Ranking of the Most Influential Persons in History</strong></p>
<p>Michael H. Hart's groundbreaking book, "The 100: A Ranking of the Most Influential Persons in History," has sparked debate and fascination since its publication in 1978. Here are some questions and answers about Hart's controversial list:</p>
<p><strong>1. What is the basis for Hart's rankings?</strong></p>
<p>Hart's rankings are based on the individuals' "impact on human history." He considered factors such as the scope of their influence, the duration of their impact, and their revolutionary ideas.</p>
<p><strong>2. Who is the most influential person according to Hart?</strong></p>
<p>Muhammad, the prophet of Islam, is ranked first on Hart's list. Hart argues that Muhammad's teachings and the religion he founded have had a profound impact on human history.</p>
<p><strong>3. Are there any notable omissions from the list?</strong></p>
<p>Some critics have questioned the absence of certain figures, such as Jesus Christ or Albert Einstein. Hart contends that these individuals are influential within their own domains but may not have had the same broader impact as those on his list.</p>
<p><strong>4. Is the list biased?</strong></p>
<p>Hart's rankings have been criticized for being influenced by his own Western perspective. However, he argues that he attempted to be objective and considered the impact of individuals on all civilizations.</p>
